data.title: Almost Authentic German  Cuisine
data.text: Considering that the Bauhaus is located in Texas and not Germany, it might be unreal to expect the cuisine to match the authenticity of true German food.  But, it is very good nonetheless.  They could use some lessons on the preparation of schnitzels.  In Germany, the schnitzel meat (pork or veal) is pounded down to a thin piece of meat that makes it more tender and enjoyable before it is cooked).  I had the Schweinsbraten w/ Dumpling & Sauerkraut, and my wife had the Jagerschnitzel.  We shared a Bavarian sausage sampler that was delectable.  And we closed out the meal with crepes drizzled in chocolate sauce with Bluebell Homemade Vanilla ice cream.  I had a Doppelbock bier and my wife had a soda.  Our bill came to $65.00 including a $10.00 tip.  The service was great.  The atmosphere is very authentic too.

data.title: Schnitzel in Aggieland
data.text: Don't let the exterior fool you.  Walked in here early on a Friday evening.  Nice interior with great German food.  Pauliner beers on tap.  Nice sized schnitzel portions and very tasty.  Great service and atmosphere.  The Nutella crepes for dessert were out of this world.I lived in Germany for a few years and this is definitely one of the better German restaurants on this side of the Atlantic.  My one suggestion for improvement is to replace the straight pretzels with German brotchen.

data.title: Nice surprise for the middle of Texas
data.text:
My co-worker and I ate here on a recent business trip.  Great place.

From the outside it looks like small town America storefront, but inside is a pretty nice looking slice of German.  Not quite an authentic beer hall, but pretty close.

I had the Jagerschnitzel, a pork schnitzel with a mushroom gravy on it.  The schnitzel was terrific, cooked just right.  Came with pretty good (but not great) spaetzle, and a little carrot salad.  I also got a side salad (not included) with a very nice ranch dressing.  Overall it was a lot of food.  Unfortunately, no room for dessert.

Our waitress was very nice.  And though the kitchen closed at 8:45, and we got there a few minutes after 8, no problem getting our food.

OK, maybe it wouldn't fool a native born German, but I would definitely recommend.

data.title: Second visit, same problem
data.text: The schnitzels are consistently over breaded and over cooked. Size is excellent; price is okay. I thought German potato salad was always served hot, but here, it's apparently refrigerated. The decor is good; the beer is mostly Paulaner varieties.

data.title: Authentic German food and dining
data.text: This is a fun place to experience some great German food, beer, and ambiance. They have several schnitzel dishes, as well as spatzle and red cabbage. The sausage platter makes a great appetizer to go with the German beer.

data.title: German-Themed Stereotypes
data.text: So the German beers are authentic, that's about it. They're good, too, although the selection could be a little more varied. The food on the other hand was not authentic, and not really a reason to go back. Overdoing the Lederhosen stereotype just a tad.

data.title: Good place to try German food and beer
data.text: A great place to go and try some schnitzel and drink some beer. My first time was during a "First Friday" in Downtown Bryan. I think that the best time to go there with family and friends since there will be live music. Try Heaven and Hell schnitzel with Pork and a Russ

data.title: Sehr gut
data.text:
Been back from Germany for about two years and this was the best schnitzel I have had.   

Recommend Monday visits as it is all you can eat schnitzels.    Didn't disappoint at all.  

Went with the mushroom gravy for the first round.  Okay but not great.   Went naked with lemon for the second.  Much better.

Pommes were good as well.  

Beer selection was okay but not great for German beers.

data.title: Taste of Deutschland
data.text: My mom and I stopped in to see if the cuisine could compare to what we used to eat in Germany. My mom had the jägerschnitzel and loved it. I had pork with gravy and want very impressed. Our server, however, barely checked on us and seemed preoccupied with her friends. Yes to the food, no to the wait staff.

data.title: As good as in Germany
data.text: Being my husband's and my families are both of German descent, and having been to Germany, we had to see if this restaurant was as good as all the locals said it is. We were not disappointed. There were three of us and each of us ordered different types of schnitzels with different sides and different beers. Unfortunately I did not make note of what each of us ordered, and cannot find an online menu, but really you can't go wrong. If it has ingredients you like, and the type of beer you prefer, you will enjoy eating here. (Although I was craving zander fish like I had in Northern Germany - hint, hint to the chef!!)

data.title: Yummy German food and beer!
data.text:
Who knew you could get tasty German food in Bryan, Texas?  We visited Germany last summer and were missing the food from the land of the World Cup winners.  We were lucky enough to stumble upon this gem, and the place was full of other diners who had the same cravings.  

The menu offers a good selection of schnitzels and brats, so it was difficult to choose.  We selected the wiener schnitzel, the jagerschnitzel, and the rahmschnitzel and each was delicious.  Served with spaetzles (small dumpling-like noodles) and some tasty red cabbage, they were juicy, flavorful, and filling. 

We enjoyed their German beer too.  We drank Oktoberfest beer and Paulaner Hefe-Weissbier, both of which were delicious.  

The server was friendly and professional.  The food came out fairly quickly considering how busy the restaurant was, and the serving size was generous.  This restaurant is on our list of favorites for the next time we're in the Bryan-College Station area.  If you enjoy brats, beer, and schnitzel, you should check out this place.  Guten appetit!

data.title: Enjoyable
data.text: Good good and service.  The portions were large and a good thing since we were hungry from not eating earlier in the day.  Definitely recommended.

data.title: Beer and ambience are great the food is just so-so
data.text: This sounded like a good idea and this restaurant was one of the only ones open the night went stayed in downtown Bryan. The beer was excellent and we were a large group so the big table was cool and reminiscent of old taverns. We had a good time and everyone seemed to enjoy their food but I have to admit, the food was not their strong suit. Maybe I just don't appreciate German food.

data.title: Very enjoyable German cuisine.
data.text:
It has been a while since we ate there, but we liked what we ordered, the traditional German wienerschnitzel and sauerbraten
with potato pancakes and red cabbage topped off with good ice-cold beer. It was delicious and we will return for more German cuisine.

data.title: Authentic food, good sized portions, tasty!
data.text: Not a huge menu but what's on it is good and it's not a wallet-buster, either!  Access to "historic downtown Bryan" kind of a plus too.....

data.title: German food restaurant in Bryan Texas?
data.text:
The atmosphere was nice, the service was excellent, the wait staff was very friendly. But German food in Bryan Texas does not fare well. I tried the Boefflamott, which is the Friday and Saturday special, the word being tried - the beef was very tough and burned/black on half on the beef. The red cabbage was ok and the wine was drinkable. I tried a piece of the Rindsroulade from my wife's plate and it did not live up to the menu description.
All in all I would not recommend the food at this restaurant unless you are from Bryan and do not expect anything better. Bryan Texas is not a German style town.

data.title: Can't handle catered event
data.text: Group of 50 was booked in for end of year event. Food was served buffet style. They ran out of plates, then ran out of food. We had to eat in shifts. No water or tea for that matter no wait staff except bar tender.

data.title: Decent German food in a pleasant atmosphere
data.text: A very friendly and pleasant place.  The German food may not be the very best I have had, but it was a welcome change and certainly tasty.  We go here often when we visit the area.

data.title: A taste of Germany - memorable!
data.text: Great local, Germany traditional food and drinks. Friendly staff. A traditional atmospherr which recreates and brings back happy memories of many a German restaurant where we ate when we lived there for several years.  Will be going back whenver we get the chance.

data.title: Not worth it
data.text: I have been here twice - the first time the table wasn't cleared off and we waited quite awhile and when I told the waiter to take away the beer she said she thought it was mine and then said I could drink it if I wanted to!  What??  The beef was very tough and couldn't hardly chew it both times I've been there - our friends and my husband didn't care for it either.
